The first virtual operator will already arrive, this year, to the Czech Republic.
Probably
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite developed and our operators offer almost all services as their partners in Western Europe.
However, here we still lack something - the virtual operator, which would force those to be cheaper.
Probably won't be long enough to get there.
That Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe, we have already written it on mobile.cz.
The rest also confirmed this by the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTú) which warned that the price of SMS messages in our country is the most expensive in the whole Union.
Following the recent steps of the European Commission in the area of roaming fees regulation, it is likely to reach a paradoxical situation - for some customers of Czech mobile operators SMS sending from abroad will be cheaper than if they send them from home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, lacks competition that really wants to fight.
This is probably paradoxical, because we have three mobile networks and their high coverage is more than 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to regret that there is extreme competition in the Czech market.
The President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTú), Pavel Dvořák, has already stated that there is no place in the Czech Republic for any other operator.
It is perhaps true that for a classic operator with his own network no longer have too many possibilities (for the rest, it would be difficult to find some frequency).
However, there is still a possibility - the virtual operator.
Precisely the entry of the virtual operator into the mobile telephony market brought a remarkable price drop before which the classic operators should also react.
At the same time, even before the entry of sharks such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile to Britain's market, voices similar to those were heard here and there.
It has been shown that there is room for such operators and that they can be successful.
On the other hand, there is no need to look for too far away examples.
In February of this year we informed you about the premiere of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
Only after half a year, this operator managed to get over 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest operator in the neighbouring country.
On the other hand, after Mobilking is the Penta group which, apart from that, in the Czech Republic is the owner of U:fon.
The advantage of virtual operators is the possibility of focusing on many more specific target groups.
In addition, so that they can function effectively, it is enough for many less customers than a classic operator.
They do not carry relatively large costs in construction, operation and maintenance of the network.
In the world this type of virtual operators are usually profiled with low costs - they offer cheap SMS calls and messages that however, often counters with the most adjusted service offer.
Thus, for example, Tesco mobile in Britain offers at least half of cheap SMS with respect to competition.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can also be a good blow to bet on a trivial target group.
This operator is specifically addressed to man.
"The right man chooses Mobilking - it's the operator who likes and whom you can trust," says David Seibert, the CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, who works this virtual operator.
It's hard to say if it looks like a Polish concept could catch up in our country.
The Vodafone spokesperson, Miroslav Čepický, doubted of this: "The Czech market is relatively small to access by segments on which most virtual operators are based.
In addition from the point of view of the supply of services is relatively saturated"
In the Czech Republic there are no possibilities, say mobile operators
However, it seems almost certain that if in the Czech Republic there will be any virtual operator that will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, however, in Czech R. doesn't seem too hopeful.
Rather, it is the launch of Mobilking in other countries in our region," he said in telephone conversation for mobile.cz, Jana Stutničková, spokesman for the Penta financial group.
Indirectly assured that current mobile telephony operators in the Czech Republic definitely do not bow to this idea.
Rather, they try to do everything possible to avoid any potential competition.
Interest on the launch of a virtual mobile operator already shows it by the group GTS Novera that I would like to take a step forward to become a real competition of Telefónica O2 in the field of business customers.
"We have a great interest in this, so that we can offer our customers not only fixed telephony services but also mobile telephony.
And the sooner, the better.
With this possibility we have met repeatedly with all Czech mobile telephony operators.
With some of them we have been able to move forward in the meetings," said group spokesman Pavel Kaidl.
So, maybe they're flashing better times.
It seems that, for non-official information, the first official operator would probably have to arrive by the end of the year.
But for now its appearance is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
"At present we believe that the situation is suitable for the emergence of a virtual operator in the Czech market.
The Czech market compared to others is a very specific market.
To date no one has been addressed to us with some complex and serious project in this field," he said for mobile.cz, Vlastimil Sršeň, spokesman for Telefónica O2.
The specificity of the Czech market refers to other operators.
The spokesperson for T-mobile, Martina Kemrová, in exceptional accordance with O2's opinion, adds: "To date we have not registered any viable commercial projects that, bilaterally beneficial, can continue to develop."
And add: "On the T-Mobile network it will be difficult to find some virtual operator until the end of the year.
At this moment we should already have on the table some concrete contracts that it would be possible to study on such short horizons"
Vodafone directs its attention to compliance with the requirements of a 3G licence.
Miroslav Čepický adds: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and this with regard to the distribution of expenditure and infrastructure.
We consider this to be the greatest contribution from the clients' point of view.
Vodafone's main strategy in this field is in the partnership with which to establish a shared network for a fast mobile internet."
Responsible offices - with uña operators and meat
Progress of mobile operators can be easily understood, but the entry of another operator would mean increasing competition which would lead to a price drop and thereby a decrease in profits.
Then why facilitate entry into competition?
When operators want to get something, they are able to pull off the same rope, proof of it is the grip when U:phone came up.
Perhaps the biggest pressure on the ČTU was at the time of the entry of U:phone by T-Mobile society.
It testifies to the public information accessible on the ČTú websites.
But precisely now U:fon serves as an argument why not accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová adds this: "Evens, not long ago the competitive environment in the mobile telephony market was opened to a fourth operator.
With regard to the nature of the market in mobile telephony in the Czech Republic, it is natural that another player's entry into the market would imply to him and, above all, to his large services requirements."
This is why this access to mobile operators is tremendously discouraging due to the absolute uninterest of the Czech regulator.
This is not just the position of the ČTU, which unfortunately has no competence to intervene in trade tenders, unlike Britain and other developed countries.
This belongs purely to the Office for the Protection of Commercial Licensing (UOHS).
However, it expressed its typical position on this issue.
"The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile telephony market would be possible after an agreement on the rental of the necessary infrastructure between a mobile telephony operator and a virtual operator was concluded.
To date no agreement has been closed since the offer of potential stakeholders rather was not interesting enough for classic operators," Kristian Chalupa, from the UOHS external relations department, added to our question.
These statements do not surprise the representatives of the operators.
For the offices that are to represent the interests of consumers, this is something more than consideration, apart from this they must observe that no one takes advantage of his position on the market.
Especially when Kristian Chalupa adds: "In abroad where virtual operators operate normally we can observe that their entry into the market contributed to the price drop of mobile telephony services"
Of course, the pressure on the correct functioning of the market and price drop does not fall within the interest of UOHS.
It is truly shocking in all this case that the sounding reactions resulting from the three mobile operators are causing.
The question of whether it really is a coincidence, is offered on its own.
It is the same as with the price of gasoline in the gas stations because it is clear that it is the work of chance and a hard fight for competition.
"The Office in this regard has not found signs of unfair competition and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position, therefore, they do not have a corresponding rise in liability in their actions on the market.
The tools needed to open the mobile telephony market to virtual operators, rather, are missing, as well as the telecommunication regulators," he added to his response Chalupa.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of the many conflicting points.
There is clearly an analysis of relevant markets developed by the ČTú that telecommunications are from the point of view of commercial tendering a single market.
None of the Czech operators have a dominant position in this type of market.
However, some of the legal experts offer another vision - for a virtual operator to emerge is always necessary to deal with the network administrator.
And the mobile telephony operator - with all his logic - has the monopoly of his network.
Therefore, in a particular segment it must necessarily be dominant.
And if this argument is not accepted, at least for UOHS should represent a warning the fact that three mobile operators are strikingly ascending in the same way.
The current complaints from stakeholders (injured by the so-called GTS Novera) show that in all negotiations with operators there are many similar impediments.
Loading responsibility in the ČTú is a rather common trick in the field of telecommunications from which UOHS washes its hands in all this matter.
We've already met with him in some similar cases.
Unfortunately a new amendment to the telecommunications law was tabled recently for the expansion of the competition of the ČTU in the field of commercial tenders that did not take effect, even though a number of specialists promised that the situation would improve.
The representatives of UOHS should know this perfectly, but it is clear that their interests are elsewhere.
It's all right, when no one looks
At the same time, unappreciatedly it still works as a pseudovirtual operator that in the Czech mobile telephone networks there already exist a few.
They are companies that put their own prices to mobile telephony services which, however, are only one part public.
These are usually companies that are engaged in multilevel marketing.
Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile phone services.
Usually only a few elected get the price list of these companies.
The magic is that the company, with respect to the operator, acts as a classic business customer of the company in charge of a large number of SIM cards.
As a special customer you will later receive special prices and other offers.
The problem is that commercial conditions in all Czech mobile operators prohibit this type of resale.
"If cases such as those cited could be found to be referred to in terms of contract conditions that could be translated into the end of collaboration with the given society," she answered the question about this problem Martina Kemrová.
But it is quite unlikely that a kind of activity carried out by mobile operators would not reach responsible people.
Precisely in the case of the three companies mentioned above may become thousands of customers.
None of the operators are against this procedure.
With the activities of these companies, they gain nothing despicable and, at the same time - unlike the true virtual operators - in no way threaten their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický warns us of the possible problems: "the law allows such speculation, however, the services of this company are only used by so much a per cent of customers.
These must also accept that your phone's SIM card is not in your name so you can't absolutely dispose of it as a normal customer of operators."
Precisely this is what should seem to the least strange ČTU.
There is also a new question for UOHS.
If mobile telephony operators surround their eyes in this type of procedure, why do they block the entry of the virtual operator?
It is necessary to add that UOHS has sufficient competence to discover these types of activities and whether it is not going to want to be content with the operators' explanations that they have no idea of this history and that their commercial conditions do not allow it.
When will we stop being the most expensive?
As was clear in the text, the entry of the virtual operator into the mobile phone market resulted in a significant decrease in service prices.
At the same time, virtually in all the countries where the virtual operator emerged, classic operators tried to protect themselves from this eruption.
The arguments used by these were practically all identical - too small, a market, eventually too saturated, problems with the quality of the service, etc.
In the most advanced countries, however, the regulatory bodies have now intervened and in none of the cases have defended operators but their customers.
Whether with formal measures or informal pressure, they made the first virtual operator emerge and with it began to arise more.
Unfortunately, the Czech Organ of Regulation all this case passes it as if it were a burning nail.
From our experience, we cannot help but be impressed that the confusion of powers in these cases suits them.
But let's not despair.
If this information between backrests is correct and the virtual operator actually reaches these lands, then the Czech market of mobile telephony is likely to start moving again.
If any of the operators let in any virtual mobile telephony operator it will be difficult for the UOHS to remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of other stakeholders.
And we may stop calling more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best
Listen to the four presentations of the new version of the Czech official anthem.
On Sunday, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek on the occasion of the official Czech celebrations presented the new official recording of the hymn Where, my home.
The new anthem recorded it by the orchestra of the National Theatre under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
There are four versions available - two versions that are Solos, one by male voice and another by female voice, another by Coro and another instrumental.
Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka are responsible for the singing.
The authors of the anthem arrangements are Otakar Jeremiaš and Jaroslav Krček.
On the iHNed.cz server you can listen to the four versions.
Bělohlávek considers this Czech national song to be one of the most beautiful hymns.
The Czech Radio has already said before that it intentionally chose for the Singing solos with representative young voices that are more expressive and popular.
"From the beginning I tried with the two and then, also, with the Choir that were fixed in the dictionary so that the text would be well understood, so that it might have consonance," he said.
The Czech official anthem celebrates next year on 175 anniversary.
The song Where, my Home played for the first time in 1834 in the tables of the State Theatre in the original Czech work Fidlovačka by Josef Kajetán Tyl and arranged with music by František Škroup.
It gained popularity and people made it their own.
The first stanza of the song after the rise of Czechoslovakia in 1918 became, naturally, a part of the official anthem.
One of the seven official symbols remained even after the emergence of the independent Czech Republic.
