We have said that it is a benign disorder, therefore it has no treatment, except that it is associated with another alteration of the dream that can be treated (for example, if it is associated with sleep apnea or a stress box).
What can be done is take into account a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child too much before going to sleep.
So look for quiet games and avoid TV shows or series that are either of fear or a little violent.
With very nervous children who are very difficult to relax, relaxation techniques can be used to help them gain some inner calm.
This will help the child to have a calmer dream.
Once the nightmares appear, try to keep calm.
Remember that they are harmless for the child and that the next day he will not remember anything that has happened.
Useful advice
Don't wake him.
It's useless, because he's not conscious, and you'll break his dream.
Although he's talking, he's sleeping and so he's resting.
Remember that if you are very distressed during several episodes you should consult or find out what it is that causes so much anxiety in the child.
If you understand what he says (which is not the most usual), do not be tempted to do an interrogation to convey information to him.
You won't get anything, because being asleep is not aware of how to organize your thinking.
You will also hear what he says, but you do not know what he is dreaming to say that, with which much care how you interpret the information and with the conclusions you draw.
Never tell the child that you can interrogate him at night to know his secrets.
Not even joking.
That generates a lot of anxiety.
In short, don't worry, it's nothing bad, it's an episode that lasts just a few minutes.
