The Bush administration and the leaders of Congress, both Republicans and Democrats, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the most important economic rescue plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the US$700 billion plan that aims to curb the financial crisis that has been shaking Wall Street for months has yet to be confirmed by both Houses of Congress.
In particular, it provides for: better control by the elected parties of their implementation, of new mechanisms to ensure the reimbursement of the invested public money, of the new provisions to contain the number of homes that are excluded from payment, as well as a right to control the wages paid to the leaders of the assisted companies.
The US Treasury Secretary, Henry Paulson, the Speaker of the House of Representatives, Nancy Pelosi, and the Republican representative at the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced the good news a few minutes after midnight yesterday, at the end of a two-day negotiating marathon.
"We are making great progress towards an agreement that will be effective in the markets," said the representative of the Bush administration, Henry Paulson.
"Everything has been done to cover the economy and ordinary Americans in the face of the current crisis on Wall Street," the Democrat explained.
"It is the fundamental point: if we do not do this, the trauma, chaos and disturbances on the daily lives of the Americans will be immense," said Republican Judd Gregg.
The negotiations had been concluded very quickly in the last few hours because they feared the effect that would result in a new failure in the mood of investors.
The last hour that had been set was the opening of the markets this morning.
The two candidates in the American presidential elections, which were late in the negotiations, were more favourable to the agreement, but nevertheless expressing their satisfaction at being forced to reach this end.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama was given certain provisions to reach the agreement, particularly the one that would allow owners to keep their home and the salary of the leaders of the state-surviving companies.
