What do they produce in the Zushlag &amp; Co. billing factory?
Very soon, on 8 October, the criminal proceedings against János Zuschlag and his accomplices will begin.
The politician and his accomplices are accused of committing significant damage fraud, in a business way, continuously and in an organized manner in addition to other crimes, including forgery of documents.
According to the Public Prosecutor ' s Office, funds obtained in public tenders have been used for their own purposes, often justifying the performance of the tasks with false invoices.
The public funds and that of the town halls - in their entirety about HUF 65 million - partly stopped in the treasury of the organization Fiatal Baloldal and in part in the pocket of private persons.
The method, which was also made known to researchers, was to justify the collection of funds obtained in public tenders with false invoices behind which there was no real execution, the different associations never fulfilled their obligations assumed.
According to the prosecution, most bills were false.
To this end, the Talonaires were obtained in the Józsefváros District market and the circular seals were manufactured in the city of Kiskunhalas.
And the question that, on behalf of which company the counterfeit invoice was to be made, was decided among other things on that tour by the Balaton Superior Region where János Zuschlag sent to István Sides.
The latter confessed that for this purpose he had to choose hostels and restaurants.
He requested an invoice for his consumption, and these served as a model for making the invoices that they presented among others in the contests of the Ministry of Youth and Sport, in the Ministry of Social and Labour Affairs, as well as in the City of Capital.
These invoices were signed mostly by István Sides and his accomplice András 'ri, who according to our information rather wrote the reports needed to obtain the public subsidies.
During one of his "study trips" Sides chose a brewery.
According to two bills issued in 2003 by Zuschlag and his accomplices, this gastronomy center provided food for a group of ninety people from the Pont Egyesület Biztos Association.
However - according to the center manager - so many people do not fit at once in that place.
Similarly, the bill issued in the summer of 2002 for the Jobb Foundation Jöv'ert - later called Együtt a Harmadik Évezredert - was full of formal and contextual errors.
For a hostel in the town of Badacsonytomaj had only three rooms and more than ten people could not stay there in one night, however the bill contained one hundred and thirty people.
But the great fancy bill manufacturers also exaggerated when they pointed to the food center Pigal Kft. for in the book store of it - according to the information given to the Prosecutor's office - there were no documents on behalf of Jobb Jövört and Hoppá.
