The intelligent car imitates the flight of the bee
What would be the best way to develop technologies in order to avoid collisions, if not the imitation of the obstacles sensors existing in nature?
For example, that of bees.
In a surprising project presented at CEATEC in Japan, the bees gave the starting point for Nissan engineers to design the next generation of collision prevention systems.
The Nissan, in cooperation with the University of Tokyo, designed the system of robotic driving cars type BR23C imitating nature, to which the characteristics of the beejorros were given, with the ultimate aim of creating a system that can do away with all collisions.
During the flight each beejorro creates its own ovaled private space that actually looks a lot like our safe capsule - explained in the exhibition Kazuhiro Doi, technological director of RP and development and research.
They play an important role in the composite eyes of bees that are able to see in all directions at an angle greater than 300 degrees.
To copy the function of the compound eyes, engineers used the laser beam length measurement system.
It identifies the obstacles in front of the BR23C within a distance of 2 meters, at an angle of 180 degrees, calculates its distance and sends a signal to the vehicle microprocessor that immediately turns into a maneuver to avoid collision.
In a fraction of seconds the obstacle is identified, then the robot of the vehicle imitating the movements of the beehives, modifying the direction by turning to the necessary extent the wheels.
Unlike any existing system, this maneuver is totally instinctive.
"If not, the robot of the vehicle could not react quickly enough to avoid obstacles" - explains Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the vehicle robot project.
It must react immediately and instinctively, as this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable inner layer of the safety protective capsule, in a layer within which all types of collisions are currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what a bee does to do away with other beeches.
This process must be done in an opening and closing the eyes.
However, unlike bees, the movement cannot turn upwards, downs or diagonally, but can only be two-dimensional and exclusively in the turn direction of the wheels
In this way, instead of the infinite possibilities that exist for bees to dodge other bees, here they only used as a possibility for the car robot the rotation movement and acceleration as well the braking.
The BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and their energy density is greater, which means that they have a longer life than that of lithium-ion.
According to Andoh, the important thing is instinctive and intelligent reaction and not data processing capacity, much less storage capacity.
This device in each second should only process some input signals and react as appropriate.
It is not necessary to store this data or react with an instinctive logic based on data from previous maneuvers, so it uses only a few tens of kilobytes of memory.
You don't need gigabytes or megabytes.
This is the first step in developing technology to immediately avoid obstacles, which according to Nissan's calculations, can be incorporated into serial-made models within ten years.
Another possibility for its application is to incorporate the unit into the GPS satellite navigation system to bring the driver to his destination, avoiding the obstacles on his way.
