"Most Gypsies have not finished middle school and due to the poor quality of basic education, only a small part can obtain university diplomas."
Jároka also stressed that education, as a fundamental human right, has a decisive role in the prevalence of other human rights as well.
Investment in the education of Roma children at an early age can strengthen the economy of the Member States of the European Union.
According to the Member of the European Parliament, these issues need to be made widely aware of both Roma and non-Gypsy issues.
As soon as the school begins, a Gypsy student will have more opportunities to become an active member of the labour market; through income and consumer taxes they will also contribute to the national budget.
"As citizens of the European Union, Gypsies must ensure their right to quality education and ensure the abolition of segregated and low-level education," said Lívia Járóka.
According to the European Parliament, the objective and active unity of the European Union is necessary to speed up the process of school segregation immediately, so it is of fundamental importance that the correct implementation of the existing and planned anti-discrimination directives should be carried out.
"The vicious circle of poverty, segregation and unemployment must be broken, and Roma children must be given the opportunity to guarantee democratic space so that they can contribute to the future of Europe as citizens of full rights," Jóróka said.
The aim of the European Summit for Equal Opportunities, organised annually since last year's Berlin meeting, held in the sign of the "European Year of Equal Opportunities", is to ensure a unique forum to promote the abolition of discrimination and equal opportunities at European and national level of the Member States.
