"A city without cinematographic halls in a blind city, is like a face without eyes."
The image offered by director Giuseppe Tornatore photographs effectively what is happening in the great Italian urban centers as well as in the cities of the province.
The process of marginalization of the cinemas, which with the birth of the great methics on the periphery and the consequent disappearance of the mono rooms in the central areas of the city, is an inevitable and indisputable event with all the characteristics of a true cultural crime.
To disappear are almost always historic places, full of memory," it's like a friend died, a known one with which a piece of place and so much emotion was shared," says the director of the new cinema Paradise, the film that 20 years ago won the cousin Oscar and the grand prize of the jury to Cannes, which counted the poetry of a provincial cinema hall and nostalgia for the way of living the movie that was lost perhaps forever.
The figures given by the Anec, the leading association of traders, speak clearly: in the last five years, 316 traditional cinemas have been closed, and the majority of the rooms in the main cities are above all the rooms in Florence: 10 less in Florence, 9 less in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most suffering from closures are as first, Emilia-Romaña with 82 lesser cinemas, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
It is a demonstration that the person responsible for his disappearance is the advent of the multiplex, it is the same three Italian regions that have recorded the largest number of new methic cinemas: 195 screens more in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in Tuscany than in Emilia-Romaña.
"The Italian exercise has been developed irrationally" notes Paolo Protti, President of the Anec," it would be useful to build new structures but it would be necessary to ensure the permanence of those already existing, because when a city hall closes, not all its frequenters are willing to transfer to the mechanics.
